      "source": "Great ‚Äî this **Part-3** version is where abstraction becomes **layered and realistic**.\nYou now have **multi-level abstraction**, **final methods**, and **safe down-casting**.\nLet‚Äôs walk through it **step by step**, from top ‚Üí bottom, and then connect everything.\n\n---\n\n# üß± Big Picture First (Mental Model)\n\n```\nAnimal (abstract)\n ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Mammal (abstract)\n ‚îÇ     ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Dog (concrete)\n ‚îÇ     ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Horse (concrete)\n ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Fish (concrete)\n```\n\n* `Animal` ‚Üí **what every animal is**\n* `Mammal` ‚Üí **what only mammals are**\n* `Dog / Horse / Fish` ‚Üí **real objects**\n\nThis is **hierarchical abstraction**.\n\n---\n\n# 1Ô∏è‚É£ `Animal.java` ‚Äî **Root abstract class**\n\n```java\npublic abstract class Animal {\n```\n\n### What Animal defines\n\n* Common state\n* Common behavior rules\n* Shared utility logic\n\n---\n\n### Fields\n\n```java\nprotected String type;\nprivate String size;\nprivate double weight;\n```\n\n* `type` ‚Üí accessible to subclasses\n* `size`, `weight` ‚Üí hidden (encapsulation)\n\n---\n\n### Constructor\n\n```java\npublic Animal(String type, String size, double weight)\n```\n\nEvery animal **must** have these values.\n\n---\n\n### Abstract methods (contracts)\n\n```java\npublic abstract void move(String speed);\npublic abstract void makeNoise();\n```\n\nEvery concrete animal **must implement these**.\n\n---\n\n### ‚≠ê `final` method (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n```java\npublic final String getExplicitType() {\n    return getClass().getSimpleName() + \" (\" + type + \")\";\n}\n```\n\nKey ideas here:\n\n| Concept           | Explanation                      |\n| ----------------- | -------------------------------- |\n| `final`           | Cannot be overridden             |\n| `getClass()`      | Runtime class (Dog, Horse, Fish) |\n| `getSimpleName()` | Class name                       |\n\nSo for:\n\n```java\nnew Dog(\"Wolf\", ...)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nDog (Wolf)\n```\n\nüëâ This guarantees **consistent behavior** across all subclasses.\n\n---\n\n# 2Ô∏è‚É£ `Mammal.java` ‚Äî **Abstract class extending abstract class**\n\n```java\nabstract class Mammal extends Animal\n```\n\nThis is **partial implementation**.\n\n---\n\n### Why Mammal exists\n\nSome behaviors apply **only to mammals**, not all animals.\n\nExample:\n\n* Dogs shed hair ‚úî\n* Horses shed hair ‚úî\n* Fish ‚ùå\n\n---\n\n### Mammal constructor\n\n```java\nsuper(type, size, weight);\n```\n\nJust passes values upward.\n\n---\n\n### Mammal overrides `move()`\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic void move(String speed) {\n    System.out.print(getExplicitType() + \" \");\n    System.out.println(speed.equals(\"slow\") ? \"walks\" : \"runs\");\n}\n```\n\nImportant:\n\n* Mammals share a **default movement**\n* But subclasses *can override it* (Dog does)\n\n---\n\n### Mammal adds new abstract method\n\n```java\npublic abstract void shedHair();\n```\n\nThis means:\n\n* All mammals **must shed hair**\n* But **how** depends on the mammal\n\n---\n\n# 3Ô∏è‚É£ `Dog.java` ‚Äî **Concrete Mammal**\n\n```java\npublic class Dog extends Mammal\n```\n\nDog must implement:\n\n* `makeNoise()` (from Animal)\n* `shedHair()` (from Mammal)\n\n---\n\n### Dog overrides `move()`\n\nEven though Mammal already implemented it, Dog **customizes behavior**.\n\nThis is legal and common.\n\n---\n\n### `shedHair()`\n\n```java\nSystem.out.println(getExplicitType() + \" shed hair all the time\");\n```\n\nDog-specific behavior.\n\n---\n\n### `makeNoise()`\n\n```java\nif (type == \"Wolf\") { ... }\n```\n\n‚ö† Same issue as earlier sections:\n\n‚ùå Wrong:\n\n```java\ntype == \"Wolf\"\n```\n\n‚úÖ Correct:\n\n```java\n\"Wolf\".equals(type)\n```\n\n---\n\n# 4Ô∏è‚É£ `Fish.java` ‚Äî **Direct Animal (NOT Mammal)**\n\n```java\npublic class Fish extends Animal\n```\n\nFish:\n\n* Implements `move()`\n* Implements `makeNoise()`\n* Does **NOT** have `shedHair()`\n\nBecause fish are **not mammals**.\n\nThis is **clean design**.\n\n---\n\n# 5Ô∏è‚É£ `Horse.java` ‚Äî **Another Mammal**\n\n```java\npublic class Horse extends Mammal\n```\n\n---\n\n### `shedHair()`\n\n```java\nSystem.out.println(getExplicitType() + \" sheds in the spring\");\n```\n\nDifferent shedding behavior than Dog.\n\n---\n\n### `makeNoise()`\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic void makeNoise() {\n}\n```\n\nThis compiles, but:\n\n* Horse is silent\n* Likely left empty intentionally for teaching\n\n---\n\n# 6Ô∏è‚É£ `Main.java` ‚Äî **Runtime polymorphism + pattern matching**\n\n---\n\n### Creating animals\n\n```java\nArrayList<Animal> animals = new ArrayList<>();\n```\n\nThis list holds:\n\n* Dog\n* Fish\n* Horse\n* Any future Animal\n\n---\n\n### Looping through animals\n\n```java\nfor (Animal animal : animals) {\n    doAnimalStuff(animal);\n```\n\nThis calls:\n\n* Correct `makeNoise()`\n* Correct `move()`\n\nBased on **runtime type**, not reference type.\n\n---\n\n### ‚≠ê Pattern Matching with `instanceof` (Java 16+)\n\n```java\nif (animal instanceof Mammal currentMammal) {\n    currentMammal.shedHair();\n}\n```\n\nWhat happens here:\n\n| Step                | Explanation             |\n| ------------------- | ----------------------- |\n| `instanceof Mammal` | Checks type at runtime  |\n| `currentMammal`     | Automatically cast      |\n| Safe                | No `ClassCastException` |\n\nThis is **modern Java**, very interview-relevant.\n\n---\n\n### `doAnimalStuff()`\n\n```java\nprivate static void doAnimalStuff(Animal animal) {\n    animal.makeNoise();\n    animal.move(\"slow\");\n}\n```\n\nThis method:\n\n* Knows **nothing** about Dog, Fish, Horse\n* Depends only on **Animal contract**\n\nThat‚Äôs **true abstraction**.\n\n---\n\n# üß† What You‚Äôve Actually Learned Here\n\n### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Multi-level abstraction\n\nAbstract classes can extend abstract classes.\n\n---\n\n### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Partial implementation\n\n`Mammal` implements some behavior but leaves some abstract.\n\n---\n\n### 3Ô∏è‚É£ `final` methods\n\nUsed to **lock down shared logic**.\n\n---\n\n### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Runtime polymorphism\n\nMethod calls depend on **actual object**, not reference.\n\n---\n\n### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Safe down-casting\n\nUsing `instanceof` pattern matching.\n\n---\n\n# ‚ö† Important Improvements (You Should Know)\n\n### Fix string comparison everywhere\n\n‚ùå\n\n```java\ntype == \"Wolf\"\n```\n\n‚úÖ\n\n```java\n\"Wolf\".equals(type)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Design insight (advanced)\n\nAvoid using `type` to control behavior.\nPrefer **subclasses** instead:\n\n```\nWolf extends Dog\nGoldfish extends Fish\n```\n\nCleaner, scalable, OOP-correct.\n\n---\n\n# ‚úÖ Final One-Line Summary\n\n> **This code demonstrates real-world abstraction using inheritance layers, shared behavior, enforced contracts, and runtime polymorphism ‚Äî exactly how professional Java systems are designed.**\n\nIf you want next, I can:\n\n* Rewrite this using **interfaces**\n* Show **interview explanations**\n* Refactor to **best-practice OOP**\n* Explain **why final is used here**\n* Convert this to **UML diagram**\n\nJust tell me üëç\n",
